column3: I wear many hats; job title is irrelevant.
column4: That depends which job.  As a software developer, I would design, plan, write, test, debug software, and also speak with beta testers to get feedback.  In IT, I am the IT guru's assistant, logging his time in/out at each client, installing software on client machines, explaining (in plain English) to the client what we are doing to their computer, and helping the IT guru in any other way he needs.
column5: See above, "the IT guru's assistant"... I also develop software for my own private project on the side.
column7: small IT company, working on site (usually in client homes)
column15: In IT we don't use CRMS.  In software development jobs, I've used ClearQuest and ClearCase at one, and less formal methods at other jobs.  In one position, I designed my own bug report form (CR).

column70:
On the bug report form that I created, I don't think I ever got one back that was filled out completely.  Usually the person reporting the bug wrote as little as they could to mention that there's a bug.  This is not very useful if they don't mention anything about how to make the bug happen, under what conditions it does or does not occur, etc.

On the other hand, I found ClearQuest difficult to use without any training.
